    module: "6", moduleContent: "Mutation",
    syllabusOutcomes: ["BIO12-6", "BIO12-12", "BIO12-13"],
    questionText: "Explain how TWO processes that affect the gene pool of populations can lead to evolution.",
    markingCriteria: "5 marks: Demonstrates a thorough understanding of TWO mechanisms by which gene pools change AND relates changes in the gene pool to evolution\n3–4 marks: Links changes in the gene pool to evolution AND demonstrates a thorough understanding of ONE mechanism by which gene pools change OR demonstrates some understanding of TWO mechanisms by which gene pools change\n2 marks: Outlines ways in which gene pools can change OR links changes in gene pools to evolution\n1 mark: Provides some relevant information",
    sampleAnswer: "A gene pool is the total genetic diversity of a population – it results in variation of phenotypes and provides the basis for natural selection. When the gene pool of a population changes evolution has occurred.\n\nGene pools may change as a result of mutation, gene flow and genetic drift. Gene flow is the movement of alleles into or out of a population. For example a migrant animal may add new alleles when it reproduces with individuals in the population. Genetic drift is a change in allele frequency as a result of random selection of alleles. This is especially marked in a small, remnant population. The few remaining individuals that survive carry a small sample of the alleles in the original population.",
